<h2>What Is Schema Therapy?</h2>
<p>Schema Therapy was developed by Dr Jeffrey Young in the 1980s and 90s as an approach for people who don't respond fully to standard CBT — particularly those with personality disorders, chronic depression, and long-standing relationship difficulties. It integrates cognitive, behavioural, attachment, and experiential techniques into a framework centred on "schemas" — deep, pervasive beliefs about oneself and the world that develop in childhood and shape patterns throughout life.</p>

<h2>What Are Schemas?</h2>
<p>Schemas are core beliefs and themes — often outside conscious awareness — about how we are, how the world works, and what we can expect from others. Young identified 18 early maladaptive schemas, including:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Abandonment/Instability:</strong> The belief that important others will inevitably leave or be unavailable</li>
  <li><strong>Defectiveness/Shame:</strong> The belief that one is fundamentally flawed, bad, or unlovable if truly known</li>
  <li><strong>Emotional Deprivation:</strong> The belief that emotional needs (nurturance, empathy, protection) will never be met</li>
  <li><strong>Subjugation:</strong> The belief that one must suppress one's own needs to avoid retaliation or abandonment</li>
  <li><strong>Unrelenting Standards:</strong> The belief that one must achieve very high standards to avoid criticism or shame</li>
</ul>

<p>Schemas develop when core childhood needs — for safety, connection, autonomy, self-expression, and realistic limits — go unmet. They feel like absolute truths rather than beliefs because they formed before sufficient cognitive development to question them.</p>

<h2>Schema Modes</h2>
<p>Schema therapy also works with "modes" — the different emotional and coping states that people shift between. Key modes include:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Child modes (vulnerable, angry, undisciplined)</li>
  <li>Critic modes (punitive, demanding — often internalised voices of critical caregivers)</li>
  <li>Coping modes (avoidance, surrender, overcompensation)</li>
  <li>The Healthy Adult mode — the goal: an integrated, compassionate, effective state</li>
</ul>

<p>A large part of schema therapy involves identifying which mode is active, understanding its origin, and building the Healthy Adult capacity to respond to it.</p>

<h2>The Three Core Techniques</h2>

<h3>Cognitive Techniques</h3>
<p>Identifying and challenging schemas through examining evidence for and against them, tracking their origins in early experience, and understanding how they operate in current relationships and situations.</p>

<h3>Behavioural Pattern Breaking</h3>
<p>Schemas maintain themselves through coping behaviours — avoidance, surrender, or overcompensation. Schema therapy directly targets these patterns, gradually replacing them with healthier responses.</p>

<h3>Experiential and Imagery Work</h3>
<p>Schema therapy is distinctive in its use of experiential techniques — particularly imagery rescripting, where clients revisit early memories with their adult self providing what was missing, and chair work, where different modes are given voice and put in dialogue. These techniques access and shift schemas at an emotional level that purely cognitive work doesn't always reach.</p>

<h2>Who Benefits from Schema Therapy?</h2>
<p>Schema therapy is particularly effective for personality disorders (especially BPD), chronic depression and anxiety, eating disorders, relationship difficulties, and people with long-standing patterns that haven't responded to other approaches. It is not a short-term therapy — courses typically run 12–36+ months for complex presentations.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>How is schema therapy different from CBT?</strong><br/>
CBT focuses on current thoughts and behaviours, typically over 12–20 sessions. Schema therapy goes deeper — to the origin and structure of core beliefs, uses more experiential techniques, and is designed for complex, long-standing difficulties. It's a longer treatment.</p>

<p><strong>Does schema therapy work online?</strong><br/>
Yes. The cognitive and mode-work components translate well to video. Imagery rescripting and chair work can also be conducted online effectively, though require a therapist skilled in adapting these techniques to the format.</p>

